{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_019KEdqsKHhWbLhUMeDwTAKz","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"All three jobs completed successfully. Here's the performance comparison:\n\n| Strategy | Elapsed | Skew Handling | Speedup |\n|----------|---------|---------------|---------|\n| **Baseline** | 31.7s | None — 44x skew ratio, max partition 10x larger | — |\n| **Broadcast Join** | 15.6s | Broadcasts small `products` table to all executors; no shuffle needed | **2.03x faster** |\n| **AQE (Adaptive Query Execution)** | 15.3s | Auto-detects and splits hot partitions at runtime | **2.07x faster** |\n\n**Key takeaways:**\n- The baseline showed a **44x skew ratio** (max partition 11,579 rows vs min 263), causing severe stragglers.\n- **Broadcast join** eliminates the shuffle entirely by replicating the small `products` table — effective when one side of the join is small.\n- **AQE** auto-splits oversized (hot) partitions at runtime with no code changes required — equally effective here and more generalizable to large-vs-large joins where broadcast isn't feasible.\n\nBoth optimizations cut runtime roughly in half on this dataset; AQE had a slight edge (15.3s vs 15.6s)."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":170,"cache_read_input_tokens":31328,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":170},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"980f2217-555f-4893-b2b2-fa14adaadfe1","uuid":"49d194f7-68a0-4ca1-a65a-07ae2813afbc","request_id":"req_011CcenwhSC2WPLMkmesYHYL"}
